---
title: NVIDIA inference coding recall
---

Q: What two questions have the closest direct evidence for NVIDIA inference roles?
A: Serialize and Deserialize Binary Tree, and LRU Cache.

---

Q: What does a public company tag prove?
A: It places the problem in a broad NVIDIA practice pool. It does not prove that this team asked it.

---

Q: What is the core LRU invariant?
A: Every live key has exactly one map entry and one list node, and list order represents recency.

---

Q: Which two structures give expected O(1) LRU operations?
A: A hash map and a doubly linked list.

---

Q: What can invalidate pointers or references into a C++ vector?
A: Reallocation, and erasure at or before the referenced position.

---

Q: Why are list iterators useful in an LRU cache?
A: Insert and erase stay constant time, and iterators to other nodes remain valid.

---

Q: What does Kahn's topological sort place in its queue?
A: Nodes whose remaining indegree is zero.

---

Q: How does Kahn's algorithm detect a cycle?
A: Fewer than V nodes are emitted.

---

Q: What are the three DFS colors for directed cycle detection?
A: Unvisited, visiting, and finished. An edge to a visiting node is a cycle.

---

Q: When is BFS the correct shortest-path algorithm?
A: When every edge has the same cost, including an unweighted graph.

---

Q: What condition does Dijkstra require?
A: Nonnegative edge weights.

---

Q: What is the stream-median heap invariant?
A: Every lower-half value is at most every upper-half value, and heap sizes differ by at most one.

---

Q: What does a monotonic deque store for sliding-window maximum?
A: Live candidate indices in decreasing value order.

---

Q: Why store indices instead of values in a sliding-window deque?
A: Indices reveal when a candidate leaves the window and distinguish duplicates.

---

Q: What is the prefix-sum equation for subarray sum k?
A: A subarray ending at prefix sum s needs an earlier prefix sum s minus k.

---

Q: Why does the usual positive-only sliding window fail with signed values?
A: Expanding or shrinking no longer changes the sum monotonically.

---

Q: What is binary search on the answer looking for?
A: The boundary where a monotone feasibility predicate changes value.

---

Q: What is the row-major offset for matrix element i, j?
A: i times the column count plus j.

---

Q: What is the general tensor element offset?
A: The sum over dimensions of index times element stride.

---

Q: What must be checked before rows times columns?
A: Shape validity and integer multiplication overflow.

---

Q: Why can tiled transpose be faster than the direct double loop?
A: A tile reuses cache lines and reduces long-stride memory access.

---

Q: What does x and x minus one do for nonzero unsigned x?
A: It clears the lowest set bit.

---

Q: What is the power-of-two test?
A: x is nonzero and x AND x minus one equals zero.

---

Q: What is the power-of-two align-up formula for unsigned x and a?
A: `(x + a - 1) & ~(a - 1)`, after guarding overflow.

---

Q: What is the quantization formula for asymmetric INT8?
A: Clamp round(x divided by scale) plus zero point to the INT8 range.

---

Q: What invalid scale must a quantizer reject?
A: A scale that is zero, negative, NaN, or infinite.

---

Q: What is the beam-search frontier bound at width B and C candidates per beam?
A: At most B times C candidates are considered at one step before pruning back to B.

---

Q: What makes sequence copying expensive in beam search?
A: Every expansion can copy a prefix whose length grows with the step count.

---

Q: What invariant must a bounded queue keep?
A: Its size remains between zero and capacity inclusive.

---

Q: Why must a condition-variable wait use a predicate loop?
A: Wakeups can be spurious, and another thread can consume the condition before this thread reacquires the lock.

---

Q: When should a producer notify a waiting consumer?
A: After changing the shared queue state while holding the mutex.

---

Q: What should close mean for a bounded queue?
A: New pushes fail, and pops drain queued values before reporting end of stream.

---

Q: What is external fragmentation?
A: Enough free bytes exist in total, while no suitable contiguous block exists.

---

Q: What does coalescing do in a free-list allocator?
A: It merges adjacent free blocks after release.

---

Q: Why is one min-heap insufficient for GPU assignment with memory limits?
A: The earliest available GPU may be unable to hold the job, while a later heap entry is eligible.

---

Q: When does a dependency-scheduled task become runnable?
A: When every predecessor is complete and its remaining dependency count reaches zero.

---

Q: What should a dynamic batcher state before coding?
A: Queue-order policy, request and token limits, deadline behavior, and tie breaks.

---

Q: What complexity should top-k over m aggregated kernel names target?
A: O(m log k) with a size-k heap after aggregation.

---

Q: What is the split-invariance property for a streaming parser?
A: Feeding the whole stream and feeding any chunking must produce the same total output.

---

Q: What four points should be said after every accepted solution?
A: The invariant, time cost, auxiliary space, and failure cases.

---

Q: What extra C++ points should be said for a mutation-heavy solution?
A: Ownership, iterator or pointer validity, allocation behavior, and overflow boundaries.

---

Q: When does a problem count as learned in this kit?
A: After a clean solve, correct complexity explanation, and a clean re-solve on a later day.

